Bedfordshire, England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Of Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1145–August 1207":"1145–augustus 1207","1145–1207":"1145–1207","1148–Male":"1148–Overleden","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1185–1260":"1185–1260","1109–1156":"1109–1156","1110–1170":"1110–1170","1110":"1110","August 1207":"augustus 1207","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1148":"1148","Abt 1156":"circa 1156","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","about 1146":"circa 1146","1109":"1109","1207":"1207","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Bedford Castle, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Of Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1145–August 1207":"1145–August 1207","1145–1207":"1145–1207","1148–Male":"1148–Deceased","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1185–1260":"1185–1260","1109–1156":"1109–1156","1110–1170":"1110–1170","1110":"1110","August 1207":"August 1207","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1148":"1148","Abt 1156":"about 1156","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","about 1146":"about 1146","1109":"1109","1207":"1207","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Bedford Castle, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","Of Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon de Beauchamp was born in 1145, in Bedfordshire, England, his father, Payne de Beauchamp, was 37 and his mother, Rohese de Vere, was 35. He had at least 1 son with Lady Isabella de Sacre le Wake. He died in August 1207, in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, at the age of 62, and was buried in Bedfordshire, England."},"et":{"1145–August 1